node.text: We sometimes use the english word "team" in French, to replace "équipe" (which is the french equivalent). So "un team de choc", or "une équipe de choc" is a kind of translation for "A-Team" or "Dream Team". But "Un team" sounds exactly like "intime", which means "intimate" or "private". And "de choc" means crack, or ace, bu the word "choc" itself means shock, or impact. So the caption sounds exactly like "A-Team" but could mean something like "intimate shock" for example. Gosh, this one was pretty difficult to explain :)
This one is a portemanteau word mixing "endormies" (meaning asleep) and "minettes" which means pussies, kitties, but also honey, sweeties... 😘💕

Les "guirlandes de Noël" is the French expression for Christmas fairy lights. For this caption, I replaced the last syllable "landes" by "langues" meaning tongues. So it's like the Christmas fairy tongues 😘💕 (ce super jeu de mots m'a été proposé par un follower, alors un grand merci à lui ! This pun was offered by a follower, big thanks to him!)
Et voilà pour 2019 ! Here is 2019! 😘💕 Thanks for all your likes!

This one will be pretty difficult to explain 😅. In the 90s in France there were very famous tv commercials, for a brand of mint sweets called "kiss cool", whose headline was "le double effet kiss cool" (kiss cool's double effect). They were so famous that, even 20 years later, the expression is still used sometimes in popular language. Now that you have the reference, I made a pun from this expression: I replace the brand name by "qui coule", meaning dripping or flow, and sounding very close. So the caption is a reference to the commercial's famous expression, but it means "the dripping double effect". Got it?
This caption sounds exactly like "avalanche" (same word in French) but is a mix between "avale" ( swallow) and "hanches" (meaning hips). So it could mean "the hips swallower"

In French, to hang onto somebody's every word is told "être suspendu aux lèvres de quelqu'un", literally "to be hung to somebody's lips". For this caption, I changed the first syllabus "sus" of "suspendu" (hung) by "suce", which means to suck. So it sounds totally like "hung to her lips", referring to the first expression, but the first word becomes a new word referring to suck. 😘💕
🇫🇷Après les lectures d'hier, un petit dessin sans titre pour une fois. 🇬🇧 After yesterday's readings, a little untitled drawing for once😘

🇫🇷J'avais gardé le contenu du livre un peu secret, voici donc un petit aperçu de ces 50 témoignages avec la très jolie histoire de Morgane, de Nantes. Je trouve cette histoire très belle, rigolote et tendre, et j'ai été très touché que Morgane me donne son accord pour la faire figurer dans le livre.
J'ai été encore plus touché lorsque Morgane est venue me voir, lors d'une dédicace à Nantes, pour me remercier et m'offrir ce cadeau très touchant : une bougie entourée d'un petit mot noué dans un ruban noir, en souvenir de son Amoureuse d'alors disparue depuis. Voilà bien le genre d'histoire que je n'aurais jamais espéré vivre lorsque j'ai lancé "petites luxures" par hasard il y a 5 ans !
(Et dépêchez-vous si vous voulez mettre le livre au pied du sapin à Noël, ce sont les derniers jours !)
EDIT : Il manque la dernière ligne du texte, honte à moi. Il faut lire ensuite "encore tous les murs de mon corps".
🇬🇧
I kept the content of the book a little bit secret until now, so here is a small preview of the 50 accounts with the beautiful story of Morgane, from Nantes. I find this story very cute, funny and tender, and I was very touched that Morgane gave me her approval to put it in the book. I was even more touched when I saw Morgane coming to me, during a book signing in Nantes, to thank me and to give me this very touching present: a candle, wrapped in a small note tied with a black ribbon, in remembrance of her Lover at that time, who passed away since then. This is the kind of story I could not hope to live when I launched "petites luxures" by accident 5 years ago! (And please be patient for the translation of the book in other languages, several different versions will be available during 2020, promise!)

🇫🇷 Sans titre nº1, acrylique sur toile, exposée le mois dernier pour la première édition de l'exposition à @acid_gallery_ 🇬🇧 Untitled nº1, acrylic paint on canvas, displayed during the first edition of the exhibition at @acid_gallery_ last month

✨ This one is also more an alliteration than a pun. The caption could be translated by something like "Hey you, starry girl". But the 3 first syllabus of the  caption ("et toi l'é") sounds exactly like the 3 last ones ("étoilée", meaning starry) so it's like a kind of phonetic repetition 😘
"Fesses" means butt. "Face" sounds quite close to fesses, and "en face" means here "across the street". So it's simply a vague alliteration to talk about a butt going across the street.

There is a French expression that does not seem to have an English equivalent, "unique au monde". Literally it means "unique in the world", but I guess that a more usual expression would be something like "the only one of her kind in the world"? Anyway, it makes references to the world, and to the fact of being unique. And for this caption, I just added a "c" before "unique" to make an hybrid word sounding like the beginning of cunnilingus. 🌍👅💕

🇫🇷 Habituellement je n'aime pas beaucoup dessiner directement à la tablette graphique, mais parfois ça donne quand même des résultats intéressants, ou tout du moins différents (et donc intéressants). Et oui, j'avais pensé remplacer également "mal" par "mâle", mais ça aurait exprimé l'inverse de ce qui est dessiné. 🇬🇧 Habitually I don't really like drawing directly with a tablet, but sometimes it gives interesting results, or at least different (and therefore interesting). Title is a wordplay with the expression "ne pas faire de mal à une mouche", which is the same in English "Wouldn't hurt a fly". I replaced "mouche" (fly) by "bouche" which means mouth. So it reads "he wouldn't hurt a mouth" 😘♥️
The title of this one is a wordplay with "costard cravate", meaning suit and tie, where I replaced "cravate" (tie) by "cravache", meaning a horsewhip 😘

Un petit collage réalisé à partir de photos collectées pour le projet @leftover_lives et visible jusqu'au 15 janvier dans la v2 de mon exposition à @acid_gallery_ à Lille. Dispo à la vente, contactez la galerie pour avoir le catalogue complet ! 😘 🇬🇧 A small collage I made from a vintage photograph collected for the project @leftover_lives and shown until January 15th in my exhibition at @acid_gallery_ in Lille. Available for purchase, contact the gallery for the full catalog. Title is a word play with "bouquet", because of the bride's flower bouquet, and because "bouquet final" is the French equivalent of the "grand finale" in the fireworks, the big surprise at the end of the show. A London friend of mine suggested me, for the English version, "Happily ever ass-ter" 😁😘♥️

This one is a wordplay with the French title of Tennessee Williams' play, "Cat on a hot tin roof". In French, the novel is titled "La chatte sur un toit brûlant" (which could be literally translated by something more like "the female cat on a burning hot roof"). "Chatte" (female cat) is also the slang for pussy. I simply removed the last "t" of "toit" (roof) to turn it into "toi", meaning "you". So, to make it short, the caption of this drawing sounds exactly like Tennessee Williams' play title, but means "the pussy on burning hot you".
(And yes, I tried new things with walnut ink and a brush on a different paper)
"Waiting for the coffee to get cold" (no pun in this one, for once) ☕

Incredible! For once, the pun of this caption can be exactly translated to English: "The jay spot". Because in French, G spot is literally the same (Point G), and the Jay bird 🐦 is called "geai", which sounds very close to the letter G. Two languages, same pun.

🇫🇷 Cette illustration fait partie de la trentaine de nouvelles oeuvres présentées à partir de jeudi dans la nouvelle version de l'exposition à @acid_gallery_ à Lille, jusqu'en janvier ! Venez venez, je serai là jeudi et vendredi après-midi pour dédicacer le livre ! Les oeuvres seront également en vente. 🇬🇧 Well, the caption of this one is about Literature. The word is almost the same in French (Littérature), and if you put a "c" in front of it, it sounds exactly like the caption of this drawing. Why a c ? Because "clit" stands for what you know, "et" means "and", and "ratures" is used to talk about crossing-outs in a text. So the sentence means "clit and crossing-outs" but sounds quite exactly like "literature".
Now put your phone down, and a book in your hand. Or your hand in your underwear. You can even do both at the same time. 😘❤️ - This drawing is one of the 30 new artworks that will be shown at the end of the week, and until January, at @acid_gallery_ in Lille. All original artworks will be available for sale, contact the gallery for more info!

Caption is a pun coming from the expression "la main dans la main", which means "hand in hand". I simply replaced the first "la main" (the hand) by "l'amant", sounding very close but meaning "the lover". So it sounds almost like "hand it hand" but means "the lover in hand".

The french expression "les deux font la paire" literally means "the two of them make the pair", I think the English equivalent would be "the perfect pair". For this caption, I replaced "paire" by "perle", which means pearl and sounds quite close. So the caption is a variation of the "perfect pair" usual expression, but means "the two of them make the pearl". (And, well, I guess I don't need to explain you the visual analogy of the pearl... do I? 😁)😘
